  "prompt": "How can you determine the derivative of [math]\\sin x^2[/math]?",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step using the chain rule:\n\n1) Let u = x\u00b2\n\n2) Then f(x) = sin(u)\n\n3) By the chain rule, the derivative will be:\n   [math]\\frac{df}{dx} = \\frac{df}{du} \\cdot \\frac{du}{dx}[/math]\n\n4) [math]\\frac{df}{du} = \\cos(u)[/math]\n\n5) [math]\\frac{du}{dx} = 2x[/math]\n\n6) Combining these:\n   [math]\\frac{d}{dx}[\\sin(x^2)] = \\cos(x^2) \\cdot 2x[/math]\n\n7) This can be simplified to:\n   [math]2x \\cos(x^2)[/math]\n\nTherefore, [math]\\frac{d}{dx}[\\sin(x^2)] = 2x \\cos(x^2)[/math]",
